Boil a half-full #kettle{}. Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{3} (or use a
#garlic press{}).

Heat the @Butter{20%grams} (see pantry for amount) in a deep #saucepan{} on
medium heat. Once hot, add half the garlic and cook for ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the @Basmati Rice{150%grams} and cook until coated, ~{1%minute}. Add
@salt{1/4%tsp} and the boiled water and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}. Once
cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Cover with a #lid{} and
leave to the side until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high
heat.

Once hot, add the @Diced British Chicken Breast{1%pack} to the pan and
season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its
> packaging.

Once the chicken has browned, add the @Tomato Puree{30%grams},
@Korma Curry Paste{50%grams} and remaining garlic to the pan. Cook until
fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @Chicken Stock Paste{10%grams} and @Water for the Curry{125%milliliters} (see pantry for amount). Bring to the boil, then lower the heat to
medium and cover with a lid.

Simmer until the chicken is cooked through and the sauce has thickened,
~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Remove the lid from the chicken curry and stir through the @Creme Fraiche{75%grams} and @Honey{1%tbsp} (see pantry for amount).

Bring the curry to the boil, then add the @Baby Spinach{40%grams} to the pan
a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Remove from the heat.

Taste the chicken curry and season with salt and pepper if needed. Add a
splash of water if it's a little too thick.

When everything's ready, fluff up the buttery garlic rice with a #fork{}, then
share between your #bowls{}.

Top with the chicken korma style curry. Enjoy!